|CKOThieves are the masters of sleight-of-hand.  If they desire something
they don't bother with formalities like asking permission from the
owner or paying for a desired item, they just take it (hopefully
unnoticed).  If they are short on cash they find an unwitting donor
and 'borrow' a few coins from them just to get them by.
hieves tend to be loners or work with others of their class, as
it seems many do not like the thieves' way of making a living.  It
is also not uncommon for there to be bounties placed upon the heads
of thieves, from their disgruntled 'victims'.
 
Because of the need to move silently thieves cannot be encumbered
with heavy armours or huge weapons.  They tend to prefer to wear
lighter armours such as leather, and carry weapons such as daggers
or shortswords.
 
Because thieves work with their hands a lot, both mental and physical
dexterity is a prime requisite for them being able to perform their skills.  
Thieves are also masters in the ability of not being noticed, so they
are very good at blending into the woodwork. Thieves also must rely on thier
intelligence to know where a rube might be and their strength to effectively
deliver blows with their weapons.

Guild levels are purchased with gold coins carried on hand.  In the
guild hall, type |BKB'cost' |CKOto see the price of your next guild level
and |BKB'advance guild' |CKOto buy it.  Your guild level must stay below
your character level.

Those new to the Thieves guild should read |BKB'thelp rules', |CKOas well as
|BKB'thelp powers' |CKOand |BKB'thelp basics'
